In April 2020, Republican-connected groups organized anti-lockdown protests against the measures state governments were taking to combat the pandemic;[584][585] Trump encouraged the protests on Twitter,[586] even though the targeted states did not meet the Trump administration's own guidelines for reopening.[587] In April 2020, he first supported, then later criticized, Georgia Governor Brian Kemp's plan to reopen some nonessential businesses.[588] Throughout the spring he increasingly pushed for ending the restrictions as a way to reverse the damage to the country's economy.[589]
